{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17506576","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17506576"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:44:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:44:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2548"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2548"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.23,0.3,0.12,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2548"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110515"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2548"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2548"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92771"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"6418"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2595"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2603"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44641"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110515"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman presents with increasing left flank pain. One week earlier she underwent a total abdominal hysterectomy for adenomyosis. She first noticed the flank pain one day after the surgery, and this improved with pain medications. However, the pain is severe now and does not improve with medications. She was discharged two days ago and ever since then, she has had this pain. She has now developed nausea and vomiting. On examination her blood pressure is 135/85 mmHg, pulse 78/min and temperature 37.1 C. Her abdominal incision is healing well and there is mild left costovertebral angle tenderness. Examination of the right costovertebral angle is unremarkable. There is no guarding or rebound tenderness. Urinalysis is normal. Serum creatinine is 79 \u00b5mol/L (45-90\u00b5mol/L).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most useful investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abdominal ultrasound","Non-contrast CT scan","CT scan with IV contrast","Retrograde pyelogram","Voiding cystourethrogram"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient with flank pain and tenderness in the left costovertebral angle after a total abdominal hysterectomy (TAH) most likely has hydronephrosis due to intraoperative ureteric ligation. Iatrogenic ureteric injury is a recognised complication associated with TAH, due to the proximity of the ureters to the uterine artery. Ligation of a ureter together with the ligation of the uterine artery would lead to ureteric obstruction. This causes the urine to backflow into the kidney, leading to hydronephrosis. Such patients usually present with renal colic pain on the affected side. The condition may go unnoticed initially due to the postoperative use of pain medications. If the iatrogenic injury is unilateral, the patient typically has normal creatinine (as in this patient) since the other kidney compensates. However, prolonged obstruction can lead to renal insufficiency. The recommended initial investigation of choice is a low dose \u003Cstrong\u003Econtrast-enhanced CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E with delayed views which may show hydronephrosis up to a transition point indicating the ligation. If there is an iatrogenic injury to the ureter, a fluid collection containing the contrast may be seen adjacent to the ureters on delayed views.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst an \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal ultrasound \u003C/strong\u003Emight be the initial imaging investigation, the CT scan will provide more accurate information about potential ureteric obstruction, perforation or hydronephrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-contrast CT scan\u003C/strong\u003E is usually preferred if the patient\u2019s symptoms are suspicious for ureteric stone. Ureteric stones tends to present with acutely severe flank pain radiating to the groin and are often associated with nausea and vomiting. Urinalysis may show microscopic haematuria. This patient\u2019s clinically significant history of recent TAH and normal urinalysis make the diagnosis of hydronephrosis more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eretrograde pyelogram\u003C/strong\u003E has been used as an investigation for urinary tract obstructions in the past. However, it has largely been replaced with ultrasound and CT scan. It may be indicated if urinary tract obstruction is strongly suspected but no hydronephrosis is seen on ultrasound or CT scan.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Evoiding cystourethrogram\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in children with hydronephrosis due to vesicoureteral reflux or posterior urethral valves.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["New symptoms after a recent procedure should be presumed related to that procedure until proven otherwise."],"references":["Morey AF, Brandes S, Dugi DD 3rd, Armstrong JH, Breyer BN, Broghammer JA, Erickson BA, Holzbeierlein J, Hudak SJ, Pruitt JH, Reston JT, Santucci RA, Smith TG 3rd, Wessells H; American Urological Assocation. Urotrauma: AUA guideline. J Urol. 2014 Aug;192(2):327-35. doi: 10.1016/j.juro.2014.05.004.","Creatinine [Internet]. The Royal College of Pathologists of Australia: RCPA, 10th January 2019. Creatinine, table 6: [Last reviewed 10th Jan 2019; cited 2023 May 30]; [Table 6, 2 pages]. Available from: https://www.rcpa.edu.au/Manuals/RCPA-Manual/Pathology-Tests/C/Creatinine","Morey AF, Brandes S, Dugi DD 3rd et al: Urotrauma: AUA guideline. J Urol 2014, 192: 327. [Ammeded 2017, 2020]. Accessed https://www.auanet.org/guidelines-and-quality/guidelines/urotrauma-guideline May 23","Goes RH,  Unnikrishnan R, Remer RN. Acute Urinary Tract Disorders. Radiol Clin North Am 2015;53:1273-92."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92771"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2548"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92771","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92771"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-31T16:37:21+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-31T16:37:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2548"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110515"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"de